    "Info.verbHistoryText" : {
      "extractionState" : "manual",
      "localizations" : {
        "en" : {
          "stringUnit" : {
            "state" : "translated",
            "value" : "`From Stardust to Speech`\n\nApproximately 4.6 billion years ago, a vast cloud of gas and dust began to collapse in a corner of the Milky Way galaxy. This primordial nebula was no ordinary collection of hydrogen and helium. Nearby supernovae, the explosive deaths of massive stars, had enriched the cloud with heavy elements forged in stellar furnaces. Among them were carbon, the backbone of organic chemistry; oxygen, essential for water and respiration; nitrogen, a building block of proteins and DNA; iron, which would form Earth’s molten core and later course through human blood; calcium, destined to become bones and shells; phosphorus, critical for cellular energy; and sulfur, gold, uranium, and dozens of other elements that can be created only in the pressures of collapsing stars or the violence of supernovae.\n\nAs gravity drew this enriched material together, the Sun ignited at the center while the remaining debris coalesced into planets. Earth formed roughly 4.5 billion years ago. Its iron sank to create a core, its lighter silicates rose to form a crust, and those supernova-gifted elements distributed themselves throughout, awaiting, across billions of years, the emergence of life that would one day use them to speak, to write, and to conjugate French verbs.\n\n`The Long Road to Language`\n\nLife emerged on Earth perhaps 3.8 billion years ago, but the journey to language-bearing creatures was immensely long. Modern humans, ~Homo sapiens~, evolved in Africa approximately 300,000 years ago. For most of that time, our ancestors lived as hunter-gatherers, slowly developing the cognitive capacities that would one day enable complex language.\n\nBeginning around 70,000 years ago, waves of humans migrated out of Africa and spread across the globe. Some traveled north and west into Europe. Others moved east across Asia. By 45,000 years ago, humans had reached the Pontic-Caspian steppe, the vast grasslands stretching from what is now Ukraine to Kazakhstan. This region, lying north of the Black and Caspian Seas, would become the crucible of one of history’s most consequential linguistic developments.\n\n`The Yamnaya and Proto-Indo-European`\n\nBetween approximately 4500 and 2500 BC, a people we call the ~Yamnaya~ inhabited the Pontic-Caspian steppe. Their name comes from the Russian word for ‘pit’, after their burial custom. The Yamnaya were among the first to ride the domesticated horse, and that skill, combined with the recently invented wheel, gave them unprecedented mobility. They were semi-nomadic herders of cattle, sheep, and goats, living in small mobile groups that followed their animals to seasonal pastures.\n\nTheir society appears to have been patriarchal and hierarchical. They buried their dead in pit graves beneath earthen mounds called ~kurgans~, often with grave goods that signaled status. DNA evidence suggests they consumed great quantities of dairy, having evolved lactose tolerance, and that they supplemented their diet with hunting.\n\nThe Yamnaya spoke what linguists reconstruct as ~Proto-Indo-European~, the ancestor of languages spoken by nearly half of humanity today. Its descendants include Hindi, Persian, Russian, Greek, German, English, and, by a long road through Latin, French.\n\nThere is an irony worth pausing on here. The very word ~French~ is not Latin at all. It comes from the ~Franks~, a Germanic people who conquered Roman Gaul many centuries later and gave their name to the land, to ~France~, and to ~français~. The story of the French verb is therefore the story of at least three peoples: the Indo-Europeans who carried the ancestral grammar westward, the Romans who planted Latin in Gaul, and the Germanic Franks whose name the language still bears.\n\n`The Verb System of Proto-Indo-European`\n\nThe Proto-Indo-European verb was a magnificent and intricate system, far richer than anything its daughter languages would keep. Verbs were built on ~roots~, compact cores of meaning, onto which speakers layered prefixes, suffixes, and infixes to express a great deal of grammatical information.\n\nThe heart of the system was ~aspect~, the shape of an action in time rather than its location in time. The language distinguished three aspects:\n\n• ~imperfective~, an ongoing or repeated action\n• ~perfective~, also called the aorist, a completed action viewed as a whole\n• ~stative~, also called the perfect, a state resulting from a completed action\n\nEach aspect had its own stem, so a single root might appear in three quite different forms.\n\n~Tense~ was secondary to aspect. Past time was marked chiefly by a prefix called the ~augment~, reconstructed as *e-, though even this was optional in early Proto-Indo-European. ~Mood~ was richly developed, with an indicative for statements of fact, a subjunctive for wishes and intentions, an optative for hopes and gentle commands, and an imperative for direct orders. ~Voice~ distinguished an active from a ~middle~, which marked an action affecting the subject or done in the subject’s own interest. This middle voice matters for the French story, because one of its endings, a passive marked with the letter r, was inherited by both Italic and Celtic, and it is among the strongest signs that those two families were once especially close.\n\n`Ablaut: The Heart of Indo-European Morphology`\n\nPerhaps no feature of Proto-Indo-European proved more durable than ~ablaut~, the systematic alternation of vowels inside roots and endings to mark grammatical differences. Ablaut was not random. It followed regular grades, an e-grade, an o-grade, and a zero-grade in which the vowel disappeared entirely, along with lengthened variants. The present of a verb might use one grade while the perfect used another.\n\nThe Germanic languages turned these alternations into the vowel changes of their strong verbs, the pattern still visible in English sing, sang, sung. Latin and its Romance descendants took a different path. Italic largely ~leveled~ ablaut, smoothing the old alternations toward uniformity, so that a regular Latin verb shows one stable stem vowel across most of its forms. Traces survived nonetheless. The perfect of Latin ~agere~, ‘to drive’, is ~egi~, with a long vowel that descends directly from an ablaut grade, and the perfect of ~facere~, ‘to make’, is ~feci~.\n\nFrench inherited a faint echo of this ancient vowel play, though most of it arose later, from Latin stress rather than from Proto-Indo-European directly. In a verb like ~venir~, ‘to come’, the stem vowel still shifts as the stress moves: je $vIEns$ but nous $venons$, ils $vIEnnent$ but vous $venez$. The diphthong rises when the syllable is stressed and falls back when it is not. The mechanism is Roman, yet the habit of letting a vowel carry grammatical weight is an inheritance from the steppe.\n\n`The Road to Italy`\n\nBeginning around 3000 BC, roughly 5,000 years ago, the descendants of the Yamnaya spread outward in wave after wave. Some moved north into the forests that would become Germanic-speaking. Others turned west and south, and among these were the ancestors of the ~Italic~ peoples, who by the second millennium BC had carried their dialects into the Italian peninsula.\n\nThe Italic languages, the family that includes Latin, share a striking number of features with the neighboring ~Celtic~ languages of Gaul and the British Isles. Both families formed certain passive and deponent verbs with that distinctive r ending. Both built a subjunctive marked by a long a. Both reshaped their superlatives along similar lines. These agreements are numerous and specific enough that many linguists posit an ~Italo-Celtic~ stage, a period after the western migrants had split from the rest of Indo-European but before Italic and Celtic themselves diverged. If that branch existed, then the ancestors of Latin and the ancestors of Gaulish were once a single community, and the later meeting of Latin and Gaulish in Roman France would be a reunion of cousins long separated.\n\n`The People Already There`\n\nThe Italic newcomers did not enter an empty land. Italy had been farmed for thousands of years, and not everyone there spoke an Indo-European tongue. The most famous of the non-Indo-European peoples were the ~Etruscans~, whose civilization north of Rome shaped early Roman culture profoundly. Etruscan was a language isolate, unrelated to Latin or to any other Indo-European language, and although it was eventually swallowed by Latin, it left its mark.\n\nA number of everyday Latin words are thought to come from Etruscan, and several of them survive in modern French. The Latin ~persona~, originally a theatrical mask and later a character or person, is widely believed to be Etruscan in origin, and it lives on as French ~personne~. ~Fenestra~, ‘window’, the source of French ~fenêtre~, is another likely borrowing. Even ~familia~, the household, from which French ~famille~ descends, is built on ~famulus~, ‘servant’, a word many scholars trace to Etruscan. These attributions are not certain, since Etruscan is still imperfectly understood, yet the pattern is suggestive. When a French speaker mentions a person, a family, or a window, faint echoes of a lost, non-Indo-European language of ancient Italy may be sounding in the words.\n\n`Early Latin and Its Verbs`\n\nLatin began as the local speech of ~Latium~, the small region around Rome, just one Italic dialect among several. The Latin of the earliest inscriptions and of the playwright Plautus, called ~Old Latin~, already shows the system that Classical Latin would refine.\n\nIn passing from Proto-Indo-European to Latin, the verb was thoroughly reorganized. The old three-way aspect system collapsed. Latin kept a present system, descended from the imperfective, and built a ~perfect~ system beside it. That Latin perfect was a genuine merger. It fused the inherited Proto-Indo-European perfect, with its stative meaning, and the old aorist, with its meaning of simple completed action. This is why a single Latin perfect such as ~cepi~ can be translated both ‘I have taken’ and ‘I took’. That double value, a completed action and a present result rolled into one form, will return at the very end of our story, when the modern ~passé composé~ takes over the work of the older past tense.\n\n`The Classical Latin Verb`\n\nBy the first century BC, the Latin of Cicero and Caesar had a verb system of beautiful regularity, and it is this system that French would inherit and slowly rebuild. Every Latin verb was organized around two stems. The ~infectum~ stem carried the unfinished tenses, the present, the imperfect, and the future. The ~perfectum~ stem carried the finished tenses, the perfect, the pluperfect, and the future perfect. Across these ran three moods, the indicative, the subjunctive, and the imperative, and two voices, an active and a passive.\n\nThe passive was ~synthetic~, formed not with a helping verb but with special endings, that same r inheritance shared with Celtic. ~Amatur~ meant ‘he is loved’ in a single word. The future too was synthetic, formed with endings such as -bo, as in ~amabo~, ‘I will love’. Verbs sorted themselves into ~four conjugations~ according to the vowel of their stem, the distant ancestors of the French verb classes. Almost every one of these synthetic forms, the r passive, the -bo future, the whole perfectum, would be taken apart and rebuilt on the road to French. The destination was not decay but a different kind of order.\n\n`Caesar in Gaul`\n\nIn 58 BC, the proconsul ~Julius Caesar~ marched his legions into ~Gaul~, the vast Celtic-speaking land that covered modern France and beyond. Eight years of war, recorded by Caesar himself in his ~Commentarii de Bello Gallico~, ended with the whole country under Roman rule and the great revolt of Vercingétorix crushed at Alesia in 52 BC.\n\nConquest was swift, but language change was slow. The Romans did not forbid Gaulish or impose Latin by decree. Latin spread because it was the language of administration, the army, trade, law, and advancement. Town by town and generation by generation, the Gauls became bilingual and then, over perhaps five centuries, Latin-speaking. Gaulish faded gradually, and there is evidence that it was still heard in the countryside as late as the fifth or sixth century AD. The Latin that replaced it was not Cicero’s polished prose but the ordinary spoken Latin of soldiers and settlers, and that everyday Latin is the true parent of French.\n\n`The Gaulish Substrate`\n\nA conquered language rarely vanishes without a trace. The Gaulish that Latin displaced left a ~substrate~, an undercurrent beneath the borrowed Latin. Its clearest gift is vocabulary. French words such as ~chêne~, ‘oak’, ~char~, ‘cart’, ~mouton~, ‘sheep’, ~bruyère~, ‘heather’, and ~alouette~, ‘lark’, descend from Gaulish rather than Latin, and many of them name the plants, animals, and rural life of the land itself.\n\nOther proposed effects are debated but intriguing. The French habit of counting by twenties, which survives in ~quatre-vingts~, literally ‘four twenties’ for eighty, is often attributed to a Celtic vigesimal system. The change that turned the plain Latin u into the rounded French u of ~tu~ and ~lune~ has likewise been blamed on Gaulish speech habits. None of these claims can be proven, since Gaulish is so sparsely recorded, but together they suggest that the Gauls did not simply abandon their tongue. They learned Latin with a Gaulish accent and Gaulish habits, and some of those habits stuck.\n\n`Vulgar Latin and the Spoken Tongue`\n\nThe Latin that ordinary people spoke had always differed from the literary standard, and after the Western Empire fell in the fifth century, the spoken language, which scholars call ~Vulgar Latin~, drifted ever further from the frozen written norm. We catch glimpses of it in misspellings, in inscriptions, and in correction lists such as the ~Appendix Probi~, which scolds writers for the very pronunciations that would become Romance.\n\nThe sound changes were profound, and they struck the verb hardest at its ends. Final m went silent. Final t weakened and fell away. Unstressed vowels blurred together and often vanished. Because Latin packed its grammar into its endings, the wearing away of those endings forced the language to find new ways to do old work. The elaborate case system, which had shown who did what to whom, collapsed, and word order and prepositions took over its job. The same erosion that flattened the noun was, at that very moment, eating into the carefully built tenses of the verb.\n\n`Inventing a New Future`\n\nConsider the Latin future. ~Amabo~, ‘I will love’, depended on endings that sound change was destroying, and worse, those endings were starting to collide with other forms and to sound like the past. A language cannot afford to confuse ‘I will love’ with ‘I loved’, so spoken Latin quietly abandoned the old future and built a new one out of parts it trusted.\n\nThe parts it chose were the infinitive and the verb ~habere~, ‘to have’. To say ‘I have to sing’, a speaker could say ~cantare habeo~, literally ‘to sing I have’. Used of things still to come, this phrase came to mean simply ‘I will sing’, and over the centuries the two words fused into one. ~Cantare habeo~ became the single French word ~chanterai~. The future of every regular French verb is still built this way, the infinitive followed by shrunken forms of ~avoir~, the modern descendant of ~habere~. You can still see ~avoir~ hiding in the endings. Beside j’ai and tu as stand the futures je chanterai and tu chanteras, sharing the very same -ai and -as.\n\nThe same recipe produced the ~conditional~. ~Cantare habebam~, the infinitive plus the imperfect of ~habere~, became ~chanterais~, ‘I would sing’. A parallel construction rebuilt the past. ~Habere~ followed by a past participle, as in ~habeo litteras scriptas~, ‘I have the letters written’, was reinterpreted as a true compound tense and gave the French ~passé composé~, j’ai chanté, ‘I have sung’. For verbs of motion and change the helper was ~esse~, ‘to be’, which is why French still says je suis venu, ‘I have come’, with être. Latin had folded its grammar inside single words. French unfolded it, leaned on helping verbs, and then, in the future and conditional, folded it up again into new single words. This rhythm, synthetic giving way to analytic and analytic fusing back into synthetic, is the deep pulse of the language’s history.\n\n`The Franks and the Name of France`\n\nAs Roman power collapsed, Germanic peoples moved into the Western provinces. In the north of Gaul the dominant newcomers were the ~Franks~. Their king ~Clovis~ united much of the country around the year 500, and his Merovingian and Carolingian successors, among them ~Charlemagne~, ruled a Frankish realm for centuries. The Franks were Germanic-speaking, yet they were a ruling minority among a Latin-speaking population, and in the end they adopted the Romance speech of their subjects rather than imposing their own.\n\nWhat they left behind is called a ~superstrate~, the influence of a socially dominant language that is given up but not without consequence. Frankish gave French hundreds of words, especially of war, rank, color, and the countryside, among them ~guerre~, ‘war’, ~garder~, ‘to guard’, ~jardin~, ‘garden’, ~blanc~, ‘white’, and ~bleu~, ‘blue’. The Germanic w at the start of such words was reshaped into a French gu, which is why Frankish ~werra~ became ~guerre~. Frankish is also the reason a handful of French words begin with a so-called ~h aspiré~, an h that blocks the usual liaison, as in ~la haine~, ‘hatred’, and ~le héros~, ‘the hero’. Some scholars credit Frankish, too, with strengthening the heavy stress accent of Old French and certain habits of word order, though such claims are harder to prove. The deepest mark is the plainest of all. The Germanic Franks gave their name to the Romance language they came to speak, and so a tongue descended from Latin is called ~français~.\n\n`The Birth of French`\n\nBy the ninth century the spoken language of northern Gaul had drifted so far from Latin that it was plainly something new. The first document to record it is famous. In the year 842, two grandsons of Charlemagne, ~Louis the German~ and ~Charles the Bald~, swore an alliance against their brother, and the chronicler Nithard wrote their oaths down. The ~Serments de Strasbourg~, the Strasbourg Oaths, preserve the words each army could understand, one version in early German and one in a Romance that is recognizably the ancestor of French. With that text, ~Old French~ steps into the light.\n\nOld French still kept more of Latin’s machinery than the modern language does. Most strikingly, its nouns and adjectives retained a reduced ~two-case system~, a ~cas sujet~ for the subject and a ~cas régime~ for everything else, the last living remnant of Latin’s six cases. The verb, too, had more distinct endings than it has today, and the ~passé simple~ was a thriving, everyday past tense. Almost everything that separates modern French from Old French follows from a single long process, the continued wearing down of unstressed syllables and final sounds.\n\n`The French Verb Since Old French`\n\nFrom the Old French period to the present, the verb was reshaped by two forces at once, sound change from below and analogy from within. As endings eroded, speakers leaned ever more on the compound tenses built with ~avoir~ and ~être~, and they smoothed away irregularities by remaking odd forms on the pattern of common ones. The huge ~-er~ class, descended from the Latin first conjugation, became the productive default. Nearly every new verb that French has coined or borrowed for a thousand years, from ~téléphoner~ to ~cliquer~, joins this class and conjugates like ~chanter~. Yet the most frequent verbs resisted the tidying, and so ~être~ and ~aller~ remain wildly irregular, je $sUIs$ and je $vAIs$ bearing little resemblance to the infinitives they belong to.\n\nA second great change was the freezing of spelling. By the seventeenth century, French orthography was largely fixed, while pronunciation kept moving. The result is the familiar gap between the written verb and the spoken one. The four forms ~je chante~, ~tu chantes~, ~il chante~, and ~ils chantent~ display four different endings on the page, yet all four are pronounced exactly alike. The grammar is still there for the eye, but the ear can no longer hear it. That silent collapse of endings set the stage for the two most distinctive features of the modern French verb.\n\n`Why French Needs Its Pronouns`\n\nLatin was a ~pro-drop~ language, one that can drop the subject pronoun because the verb ending already carries it. ~Canto~ needs no separate word for ‘I’. The ending says it. Spanish and Italian, which kept their Latin endings distinct, remain pro-drop to this day. Italian ~canto~ by itself means ‘I sing’, and Spanish ~hablamos~ by itself means ‘we speak’.\n\nFrench lost this freedom, and sound change is the reason. When the endings of ~je parle~, ~tu parles~, ~il parle~, and ~ils parlent~ all fell silent and merged into a single spoken form, the verb could no longer tell a listener who the subject was. Something had to. The subject ~pronoun~, once optional and emphatic, became obligatory, and it was bound so tightly to the verb that some linguists now treat ~je~, ~tu~, and ~il~ as little more than prefixes of person, the very work that Latin endings had once done at the other end of the word. French had become a ~non-pro-drop~ language. Where the Roman said ~cantamus~ in one word, the French speaker must say two, ~nous chantons~, and in everyday speech will often not say even that.\n\n`The Rise of On`\n\nThat last twist concerns the word ~nous~, ‘we’. In ordinary spoken French, ~nous~ and its ending -ons are quietly retreating, pushed aside by an unexpected substitute, the little pronoun ~on~. ~On~ began as an indefinite subject meaning ‘one’ or ‘people’, much like English ‘one’ or German ~man~, and it descends, fittingly, from the Latin ~homo~, ‘man’, the same word that gave French ~homme~. The word for ‘man’ became the word for an unnamed ‘someone’, and then, in casual speech, the word for ‘we’.\n\nToday a French speaker is far more likely to say ~on chante~ than ~nous chantons~, ~on a mangé~ than ~nous avons mangé~, ~on y va~ than ~nous y allons~. Because ~on~ is grammatically third person singular, it takes the same verb form as ~il~ and ~elle~, and so the spoken language quietly drops yet another distinct ending, the -ons of the first person plural. One small clue gives the game away. When ~on~ really means ‘we’, the adjectives and participles that follow it agree in the plural, as in ~on est contents~, ‘we are happy’, with an s that a true third person singular would never call for. The grammar of the ear has moved on, even as the grammar of the page keeps ~nous~ in place.\n\n`The Death of the Passé Simple`\n\nThe other great casualty of spoken French is an entire tense, the ~passé simple~. For most of the language’s history this was the ordinary narrative past, the tense in which stories were told. Today it has all but vanished from speech. Its work has passed to the ~passé composé~, the compound past built with ~avoir~ or ~être~, the very construction that spoken Latin had invented centuries before. A modern speaker says ~j’ai chanté~, not ~je chantai~.\n\nTwo pressures killed it. One was difficulty. The passé simple has irregular, hard-to-predict stems for many common verbs, and once it left daily speech, each generation learned it less securely. The other was ~ambiguity~ bred by sound change. As endings eroded, passé simple forms began to collide with other tenses. The form ~choisis~ is the plainest example. ~Je choisis~ can mean ‘I choose’, in the present, or ‘I chose’, in the passé simple, with nothing in the sound to tell the two apart. A past tense that can no longer be heard as past is a past tense in trouble. The passé simple survives today mostly in literature, in history, and in formal writing, a tense one reads far more often than one hears, much as the Latin perfect long ago split its two meanings between a completed action and a present result.\n\n`The Verb System Today`\n\nModern French keeps the broad frame it inherited from Latin, an indicative, a subjunctive, a conditional, and an imperative, set across present, past, and future. Yet almost every piece has been rebuilt:\n\n• the ~future~ and ~conditional~ are the old infinitive fused with ~avoir~, so ~chanterai~ carries ~habere~ inside it\n• the ~passé composé~ is ~avoir~ or ~être~ plus a participle, and it has driven the ~passé simple~ out of speech\n• the ~passive~ is no longer the Latin r ending but ~être~ plus a participle, as in il est aimé, ‘he is loved’\n• the ~subject~ must now be spoken, since the endings that once named it have fallen silent, and in everyday talk ~on~ is quietly replacing ~nous~\n\nThe synthetic Latin verb, which folded tense, mood, person, and voice into a single sculpted word, has become a more analytic French verb that spreads the same information across pronouns and helping verbs, even as the future and conditional show that French can still fuse new forms of its own.\n\nWhen you conjugate a French verb, when you say ~je chante~, ~je chanterai~, ~j’ai chanté~, you are handling parts of enormous age. The ending of ~chanterai~ is a worn-down Roman ~habere~. The ~j’~ you must set before ~ai~ stands in for an ending that sound change rubbed away. The bones of the words are Latin, carried into Gaul by Caesar’s soldiers, colored by the Gaulish the Gauls never quite forgot, and renamed by the Frankish kings who learned to speak them. Behind the Latin lies the steppe, the Yamnaya herders and their Proto-Indo-European. Behind the steppe lies the slow kindling of life on a planet made of stardust. To conjugate ~chanter~ is to set in motion a machine five thousand years in the building, assembled on the grasslands north of the Black Sea, carried to a small town in Latium, marched into Gaul, and still, on the tongues of millions across the world, singing."
          }
